PSEUDOCODE
==========

Initialize SysTick, USART2 TX, PA5 LED, PC13 Button
Initialize EXTI on PC13 falling edge

Seed a simple LFSR with a non-zero value (random number generator)

In EXTI ISR:
    Clear FPR1
    Set btn_flag = 1

In main loop:

    If btn_flag set:
        Clear btn_flag
        Debounce via ms_ticks
        If button still held:
            Generate next LFSR value
            Extract printable ASCII character from it (range 33–126)
            Send character + context string over UART
            Toggle LED to give visual feedback
        Wait for button release

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA2   ->  USART2_TX (AF1)   - transmit to terminal
PA5   ->  LED (GPIO output) - visual feedback on button press
PC13  ->  User Button       - falling edge EXTI

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* LFSR state must never be zero. A Galois LFSR with state 0 produces 0 forever,
  the feedback polynomial has nothing to work with. Always guard against zero
  after any XOR operation that modifies the seed.

* sw_div called twice for quotient and remainder separately. In
  usart2_send_uint, the current code calls sw_div once for the remainder and
  once for the quotient. Combine into one call by capturing both return value
  and rem in a single pass, saves one full division loop per digit. Shown
  correctly in lfsr_to_printable_ascii which uses a single call.

* WFI with a pending flag, wfi sleeps until an interrupt fires. If button_flag
  is set and we enter wfi before checking it, we sleep until the next interrupt,
  potentially missing a fast double-press. The flag check comes before wfi in
  the loop so this cannot happen here, but be aware of the ordering.

* LFSR seed variation at boot is weak, XORing with ms_ticks after 5ms gives very
  little entropy. Every boot produces nearly the same sequence. This is fine for
  a character-sending demo but not for anything security-related. A proper
  entropy source would be ADC noise sampled at startup.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* Galois vs Fibonacci LFSR. There are two common LFSR topologies. Fibonacci
  shifts the register and XORs selected tap bits to produce the feedback
  bit. Galois (used here) XORs the feedback into multiple internal positions on
  the same clock, it is faster in software because it is a single XOR with a
  constant mask versus multiple bit extractions. Both produce the same
  maximal-length sequence for the same polynomial.

* Why printable ASCII range 33–126. ASCII 0–31 are control characters (newline,
  tab, bell, etc.) that would clutter or confuse a terminal. ASCII 32 is space,
  technically printable but visually invisible. ASCII 33 (!) through 126 (~) are
  all visible, typeable characters. 127 is DEL. So 33–126 gives 94 clean
  printable characters, hence % 94 + 33.

* This program validates the full EXTI->ISR->flag->main pipeline. Every program
  from here that uses interrupts follows this exact shape: ISR sets flag, main
  loop checks flag, acts, clears flag. Program 13 (UART RX interrupt) applies
  the identical pattern to UART. The pipeline is always the same, only the
  peripheral changes.
